The photo was shared here on Facebook on February 24, 2021 by Free Youth, a youth-led anti-government group. It has been shared more than 43,0000 times.

The post’s Thai-language caption reads: “BREAKING NEWS: according to Khao Sod Online, Prime minister of Thailand, Gen. Prayut Chan-ocha, is holding a meeting with military-appointed foreign minister of Myanmar, Wunn Maung Lwin, at Don Muang airport. This makes Thailand the first country to accept internationally condemned Myanmar junta government’s diplomatic visit.”
General Prayut Chan-O-Cha is Thailand’s prime minister and former army chief who seized power from the democratically-elected government in 2014.
Wunna Maung Lwin is Myanmar’s minister of foreign affairs, appointed by the junta following a bloodless coup on February 1, 2021 which saw civilian leader Aung San Suu Kyi ousted from power.

The misleading post circulated online as Maung Lwin held talks with his counterparts from Thailand and Indonesia in the first known face-to-face meetings between a senior junta member and foreign government officials.
The photo was also shared hehttps://archive.is/gmXMtre by Pakornwut Udompipatskul, an MP from the opposition Move Forward Party in a tweet shared more than 8,000 times.
The image was shared in other posts with a similar claim here, here and here on Facebook and here, here and here on Twitter.
The photo, however, has been shared in a misleading context.
While the Thai prime minister did meet Myanmar’s foreign secretary on February 24, 2021, Myanmar local media reported here, the photo does not show the event.
The image actually shows Prayuth meeting Secretary-General Distat Hotrakitya at the Royal Thai Police headquarters in Bangkok.
Prayuth was set to chair a meeting of the police committee at the National Police Headquarters on February 24, 2021 at 2pm, local media reported.
The photo shows the headquarters of the Royal Thai Police in the background.
Various corresponding features are visible in both the photo in the misleading posts and and an image of the building on Google Maps, as shown in the image comparison below:
Contacted by AFP, the Royal Thai Police’s spokesman Yingyos Thepjamnong said the image in the misleading posts was taken at the Royal Thai Police headquarters.
“The Prime Minister was at the headquarters of the Royal Thai Police to hold a meeting of the police committee,” he said by phone on February 25, 2021.
Yingyos identified the man mistaken for Myanmar’s foreign minister as Distat Hotrakitya, the secretary-general to the prime minister.
“He is the one bowing to the Prime Minister Prayuth,” he said.
Police TV, an official television channel of the Royal Thai Police broadcasted a livestream on Facebook on February 24, 2021 showing Prayuth entering the Royal Thai Police headquarters building.
The video shows Distat, wearing a grey suit and yellow tie, walking behind him at the three-minute 41-second mark.
